concept_explanation.set_variants:
**Choosing within Set:**

| | HashSet | LinkedHashSet | TreeSet |
|--|---------|---------------|----------|
| Add/contains | O(1) ✅ | O(1) ✅ | O(log n) |
| Iteration order | Unpredictable | Insertion order | Sorted |
| **Use when** | Default — membership | Dedup preserving order | Sorted unique elements |

```java
// HashSet — default, fastest
Set<String> visited = new HashSet<>();

// LinkedHashSet — dedup that preserves first-seen order
Set<String> uniqueInOrder = new LinkedHashSet<>(list);

// TreeSet — sorted unique elements
Set<Integer> sortedUniqueScores = new TreeSet<>(scoreList);
```

concept_explanation.common_antipatterns:
**The 5 Collection Antipatterns — recognize and fix:**

**1. List when Set is needed (membership check)**
```java
// BAD: O(n) contains
List<String> seen = new ArrayList<>();
if (!seen.contains(item)) seen.add(item);

// GOOD: O(1) contains
Set<String> seen = new HashSet<>();
seen.add(item);  // auto-deduplicates
```

**2. List when Map is needed (lookup by key)**
```java
// BAD: O(n) scan
User found = null;
for (User u : users) { if (u.getId().equals(id)) { found = u; break; } }

// GOOD: O(1) get
Map<String, User> byId = new HashMap<>();
User found = byId.get(id);
```

**3. Manual duplicate tracking instead of Set**
```java
// BAD: if-check before every add
if (!list.contains(item)) list.add(item);

// GOOD: Set handles it
Set<String> items = new HashSet<>();
items.add(item);  // does nothing if already present
```

**4. HashMap key without hashCode/equals**
```java
// BAD: custom object key with no hashCode
Map<Product, Integer> stock = new HashMap<>();
stock.put(new Product(101), 5);
stock.get(new Product(101));  // returns null! different hashCode

// GOOD: override hashCode and equals in Product
```

**5. ArrayList declared as ArrayList (not List)**
```java
// BAD: locked into ArrayList
ArrayList<String> names = new ArrayList<>();

// GOOD: programmed to interface
List<String> names = new ArrayList<>();
```

concept_explanation.nested_collections:
**Nested collections** — combining collection types:

**Map of Lists (grouping)**:
```java
// Products grouped by category
Map<String, List<Product>> byCategory = new HashMap<>();
for (Product p : products) {
    byCategory.computeIfAbsent(p.getCategory(), k -> new ArrayList<>()).add(p);
}
// Access: byCategory.get('Electronics') → List<Product>
```

**Map of Sets (unique association)**:
```java
// Tags per article (each article's tags are unique)
Map<String, Set<String>> articleTags = new HashMap<>();
articleTags.computeIfAbsent(articleId, k -> new HashSet<>()).add(tag);
```

**Set of Maps (unique records)**:
```java
// Less common — usually objects are better
// Map<String, Object> as a 'row' — prefer a proper class
```

**List of Lists (2D structure)**:
```java
List<List<Integer>> matrix = new ArrayList<>();
matrix.add(Arrays.asList(1, 2, 3));
matrix.add(Arrays.asList(4, 5, 6));
int cell = matrix.get(0).get(1);  // 2
```

**Navigation**: just chain the method calls. `map.get(key).get(i)` or `map.get(k1).get(k2)`. Always check for null on intermediate results.

step_by_step_solution.details:
```java
// Need: unique codes, fast membership check — Set!
Set<String> activeCodes = new HashSet<>();
activeCodes.add("CS101");
activeCodes.add("MATH202");

boolean isActive = activeCodes.contains("CS101");  // O(1)
```
**Why not List?** `list.contains()` is O(n). With hundreds of courses, every check would scan all of them. HashSet → O(1).

```java
// Need: ordered (registration order), duplicates unlikely but possible — List!
List<String> myCourses = new ArrayList<>();
myCourses.add("CS101");
myCourses.add("MATH202");
myCourses.add("ENG301");

// First registered:
String first = myCourses.get(0);  // CS101
```
**Why not Set?** Sets have no guaranteed order. If the student cares about registration sequence, List is correct.

```java
// Need: lookup by ID key — Map!
Map<String, Student> studentById = new HashMap<>();
studentById.put("S2024001", new Student("Aisha", "CS"));

Student s = studentById.get("S2024001");  // O(1)
```
**Why not List?** You'd have to scan all students for the matching ID — O(n). HashMap gives O(1).

```java
// Need: frequency counting by course — Map<String, Integer>!
Map<String, Integer> enrollment = new HashMap<>();
// When student registers:
enrollment.put(courseCode, enrollment.getOrDefault(courseCode, 0) + 1);

int cs101Students = enrollment.get("CS101");  // instant
```

```java
// Need: department → students (multiple), sorted — Map<String, TreeSet<String>>!
Map<String, TreeSet<String>> byDept = new HashMap<>();
// When student joins department:
byDept.computeIfAbsent(dept, k -> new TreeSet<>()).add(studentName);

// Access CS department students in alphabetical order:
TreeSet<String> csStudents = byDept.get("CS");
// Already sorted!
```
**Why TreeSet inside?** TreeSet keeps names sorted automatically. No need to sort before display.

```java
// Each student has a Set<String> of course codes
Set<String> aishaCourses = new HashSet<>(Arrays.asList("CS101", "MATH202", "ENG301"));
Set<String> rajCourses   = new HashSet<>(Arrays.asList("CS101", "PHY101", "MATH202"));

// Intersection
Set<String> common = new HashSet<>(aishaCourses);
common.retainAll(rajCourses);
// common = {CS101, MATH202}
```
**Why Set?** Set intersection is clean and O(n). Doing this with Lists would be O(n²).

worked_example.final_code:
import java.util.*;

class Student {
    String id, name, department;
    Set<String> courses = new HashSet<>();
    List<String> courseOrder = new ArrayList<>();  // registration sequence

    public Student(String id, String name, String department) {
        this.id = id; this.name = name; this.department = department;
    }

    public void registerCourse(String code) {
        courses.add(code);
        courseOrder.add(code);
    }

    public Set<String> commonCoursesWith(Student other) {
        Set<String> common = new HashSet<>(this.courses);
        common.retainAll(other.courses);
        return common;
    }
}

public class RegistrationSystem {
    private Map<String, Student> byId = new HashMap<>();
    private Map<String, Integer> enrollment = new HashMap<>();
    private Map<String, TreeSet<String>> byDepartment = new HashMap<>();
    private Set<String> activeCodes = new HashSet<>();

    public void activateCourse(String code) { activeCodes.add(code); }

    public void register(Student s, String courseCode) {
        if (!activeCodes.contains(courseCode)) {
            System.out.println("Invalid course: " + courseCode); return;
        }
        byId.put(s.id, s);
        s.registerCourse(courseCode);
        enrollment.put(courseCode, enrollment.getOrDefault(courseCode, 0) + 1);
        byDepartment.computeIfAbsent(s.department, k -> new TreeSet<>()).add(s.name);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        RegistrationSystem sys = new RegistrationSystem();
        sys.activateCourse("CS101"); sys.activateCourse("MATH202"); sys.activateCourse("ENG301");

        Student aisha = new Student("S001", "Aisha", "CS");
        Student raj   = new Student("S002", "Raj",   "CS");
        Student priya = new Student("S003", "Priya",  "Math");

        sys.register(aisha, "CS101"); sys.register(aisha, "MATH202");
        sys.register(raj,   "CS101"); sys.register(raj,   "ENG301");
        sys.register(priya, "MATH202");

        System.out.println("CS101 enrollment: " + sys.enrollment.get("CS101"));
        System.out.println("CS dept (sorted): " + sys.byDepartment.get("CS"));
        System.out.println("Aisha+Raj common: " + aisha.commonCoursesWith(raj));
        System.out.println("Aisha order: " + aisha.courseOrder);
    }
}
